I made this mount to act as an additional insulator for mounting on metal. Afterwords...I actually mounted it to plywood --- but hey, it looks pretty cool anyway.

description.text:
This is a remix of johann517's excellent G-Clamp (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1673030). I've made the clamp double-sided and added a ring that can be used to hang it (e.g. suspend from a ceiling).

It's useful for all sorts of things! You can extend-a-shelf from basically anywhere it can clamp on to. You can also use it to hang things up in your kitchen, garage, etc by clamping it where you want and then clamping the thing to the other side of the clamp.

It can also be used to chain things together! If you use the ring to hang something from a ceiling, for example, you could then chain those things together by clamping each side of the thing you're hanging one to the next, to the next, so on and so forth.

Example usage:

  • Hang boards from the ceiling to make a really, really long shelf.
  • Chain-hang LED light bars.
  • Use it in the kitchen to attach a cookbook or tablet to your cabinets for easy viewing.
  • Hang parts up to dry.
  • Use it as a regular G-clamp (which is actually just a C clamp =).
  • Attach signage... Wherever!

This is a remake of the fan duct for cooling the E3D All metal hot end.
It has the same basic shape as the official one but was modeled from scratch in SolidWorks.
The internal transition is a bit smoother and the fan hole spacing has been adjusted to fit a bit better.

The screw holes for mounting the 30mm fan are sized for M3x16 machine screws.

I printed this with 4 perimeter layers.

50% rectilinear infill
I also print them at least 2 at a time to make sure there is enough time for layers to cool.

I designed this for a UM2 clone I’m building (tall mount version). I don’t like the mega bracket that's in the UM2 collection I’m using. It has sides that limits airflow, it takes forever to print, and it’s overbuilt. This design places the USB connector at the correct height to clear the clone’s aluminum frame (when using a 6mm/0.25in bottom panel).

The bracket pilot holes are 2mm or 2.5mm. These holes can be drilled out/tapped to whatever final size you desire. Even though the Mega board holes are 3.2mm, I’ve noticed that M2.5 is largest screw head that the two Mega boards I have support (all holes).

The 2.5mm and tall versions take M2.5 threaded screws without any modification.

The tall version is 16mm, the other versions are 12mm.

The tall version has an additional mount for a DC-DC bracket.
See http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2232850 for the DC-DC converter bracket.

description.text:
Fabricate "Side-A" and "Side-B". Also make the "Snap" piece which you can friction fit or glue into the slot on the Side-B shell. Adjust the depth of this piece so that when Side-A is mated to Side-B it is held snug.

Press fit and glue 4 small pins into the alignment holes on the Side-B shell. I used 4d finish nails cut down to size.

The included STL files here are for fitting into a BT-20 tube. After fitting, tape may be used to affix the casing by wrapping the shoulder and the tube. To use as a nosecone, the fitting tube should have a bulkhead and eyelet that's tied to the shock cord. Also additional centering rings on the tube will allow it to fit snugly into a larger rocket body. Alternatively, print the Customizable Rocket Nose Cone Coupler: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2302595 and screw in an eyelet.

title: Cohesion3D GLCD cabinet for K40 laser engraver

description.text:
UPDATE 6/30/17: I added (2) more versions, 1 with slightly recessed text (for single extruder) and 1 with no text for printing upside-down, flat.

I recently added a Cohesion 3D Mini motion controller to my Chinese K40 laser cutter engraving machine. This is possibly the best upgrade for your K40 and it's only about $100 US. You can buy one at: www.cohesion3d.com

A great benefit of the C3D board is the ability to add an LCD display; this is designed to be a mounting "cabinet" for a RepRap Discount/Sainsmart 12864 LCD panel. I designed this to allow for a simple, damage-free installation of the LCD and added a space for a digital temperature meter as well to monitor your coolant temperature.

I printed this on my UM3E using PLA+ at .15mm, 40mm/sec with support and brim. It took about 15 hours to print, top-side up with 2 colors. Please experiment with layer height and speed and share your results.

The first 3 files are available for both single and dual extruder printers. The 4th file is the mounting clip.

Human holo cellular retinol-binding protein II (CRBP-II). Retinol-binding proteins (RBP) are a family of proteins with diverse functions: http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Retinol_binding_protein This model is based on Protein Data Bank entry 2RCT: http://www.rcsb.org/pdb/explore.do?structureId=2RCT STL file created using VMD: http://www.ks.uiuc.edu/Research/vmd/ The protein backbone is represented in "cartoon" form. There are two STL files, one for the protein and one for retinol. The retinol component should slot into the protein model with minimum distortion. Several views of the model are provided to show how retinol should fit.

I came across the Yet another dispenser for filament spools
by Think_3D and the SIMPLE SPOOL HOLDER FOR MENDEL which I liked very well but it had some problems. The main problem was due to the fact that the spool is so low and far back that the filament would rub against the threaded bar which was not good. There are quite a number of different solutions to this problem, mine was the Mendel Filament Guide which is the ancestor of this thing. It snapped onto the top of the Mendel and allowed using left over round bar as a guide so the filament didn't rub against the threaded bar. This served its purpose but as one Thingiverse user pointed out required round bar that he didn't have on hand. It also proved something else; my snapin design worked very well. Then a couple of weeks ago I saw the Over The Top Spool Holder V2 by BackyardWorkshop and thought that this was very similar to my snap-on filament guide. I especially liked the idea that the spool was mounted above and not as far behind such that the filament went straight down. That thing had to be held by M8 nuts and I thought I could improve upon that so I started with my Mendel Filament Guide thing and then decided where I wanted the center of the filament spool to be relative to the guide holder and put it there. Then I added to circular support struts such that the snap-in capability wasn't lost and then added a support circle with the RepRap LOGO.

Print out one left spool holder and one right spool holder and snap into the inside of the top frame vertices by sliding the long hook to the front threaded bar and pressing on the rod holder to snap onto the back threaded bar. To remove grab entire spool holder with one hand down low and pull up and back. Print out two wheels, pop one 608 bearing into each of the wheels.
Cut a piece of threaded bar to a length of 24cm.
Put one wheel into each side of a standard filament spool.
Put the threaded rod through the bearing with the same amount sticking out of both sides. On each side add an 8mm washer, 8mm nut, 8mm nut, 8mm washer, 8mm washer and an 8mm nut. The inside nuts should be make tight enough to hold the two wheels in. The second set of nuts should be 1 cm from the nuts just tightened with the following washer right next to it. The last set of nuts should be as close to the end of the threaded bar as possible with its matching washer right next to it.
Now center the threaded bar onto the Mendel snap-in filament spool holders and by hand tighten the second set of nuts to the inside of the filament spool holders. Now tighten the outside nuts to the outside of the filament spool holders. Tighten with a wrench.

description.text:
This is a FPV mount for the Blade 180 QX, transforming it into a fun FPV platform. Mine weighs just under 2 grams when printed. The 180QX flies great as pictured.

Some design considerations included:

  • Can be applied and removed without tools via the canopy mounts
  • Camera can be mounted to preserve the 180QX center of gravity. This keeps motor load even and helps maintain agility.
  • Easy print, no supports needed.
  • Honeycomb matrix design provides many benefits
    • Excellent strength/weight
    • Flexible mounting options: use zip ties, tape or other 3d printed parts
    • Excellent heat dissipation for the main board and ESCs
    • Can route a 1.25 JST plug through the holes for convenient hookup to the 180QX accessory power pins

Also included is a 20 degree mounting pegs for small cameras. Consider them optional (see photos). You will need two if you decide to use them.

Note that the 180QX is rated for 17 grams of payload - I've flown with more but it loses much agility. The setup as-pictured add about 7 grams and the 180QX carries it easily. My flight times ~ 9 minutes (stock) to ~ 6 minutes fully equipped and camera set to 25 mw.

Important: Cut small pieces of thin foam (or equivalent) and glue them to the 4 mounting pegs. This ensures a secure fit and helps absorb vibration (to reduce "jello" effect).

You may want to open up the mounting holes a bit with a drill bit - use your hand to operate the bit.

Note the 180QX can easily power your camera from it's accessory port. This is "the way to go" if you can manage it because you don't have to carry an extra battery or worry about your camera battery depleting separately. I built a JST -> MicroJST converter cable to connect mine.

The camera I'm using is an Eachine TX03. Just about any lightweight camera should work fine.

title: Adjustable RC Airplane/Aircraft Propeller Ceiling Hanger for the Hangar
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
A set of hooks that slide on rails that allow you to hang most size RC Airplanes from the ceiling safely. A full set is one of each hook and two of the rails. I do not recommend these for planes with rubber bands or o-rings holding the props on or flimsy props. I'm sure there are a lot more uses than just hanging planes from. The two planes behind my design in the second pic are hanging from http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1093029.

Update #1 - I have a lot of MakerGeeks Crystal Yellow PETG so I printed a set using it. It slides together without any oil needed. I added 3 pics with a Rare Bear hanging from them. You need to leave a space between the rails for that spinner.

Update #2 - A friend had to move and couldn't bring his planes, so I ended up buying 17 planes. That included many I had owned and sold in the past. The CZ Scimitar I sold because it was so hard to store. Not anymore! See the new pic of it hanging in the basement. With the hooks I have been able to add a lot of planes to the collection and keep them all around the basement and out of sight of my wife. She even bought me a massive dehumidifier for the basement to keep the planes rust free and in shape.

Printer:

RapidBot 3.0

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

.2

Infill:

20%

Notes:

For these I use:

Honeycomb Infill
4 parameters
4 solid top and bottom layers
MakerGeeks 1.75 PETG

Oil for movement

The rails and hooks are a very tight fit if you are over extruding. Before putting the hooks on the rails I have been putting oil on the rails to ensure I can move the hooks on the rails. Without the oil (Liquid Bearings, 3 in 1, or other hobby oil) the hooks are really hard to move.

Update: After getting some bridge tests to print, I no longer need to oil my rails

Hanging Planes by the Prop

I love my plane collection but was running out of room. I have an empty section of mostly unfinished basement that used to hold a huge old furnace and two oil tanks. I've been keeping a few bigger planes on the floor there but there was so much wasted space. I downloaded and printed two of the Flugzeug Halter - Breit STLs in the Model Plane Ceiling Hooks thing from dschiedsch. They worked but were a tight fit for some planes when I tried them out. That is when I decided to make something adjustable to fit any single two blade prop RC plane and keep the hooks as close to the motor as possible where the props are stronger.

I started from scratch using Sketchup and just kept playing with the design until I had something I liked and worked. The hook and rail connection is a very tight fit. That is intentional as I did not want wander through my walk-in plane closet and bump things off the ceiling. Between the rail base to under the T-ish part I have been using Liquid Bearings along the inside corners and then working the hook back and forth a few times to make the hooks slide smooth. Without the oil, the hooks are extremely hard to slide. Even with the oil you might need to use two hands to slide one. Because I printed the rails standing up the grain of the two parts are going against each other which makes the plastic click for each layer it moves. This is an unintentional effect, but I like it.

Rail Spacing

As you can see in the pictures with the Carbon-Z Cub, I mounted my first one with the two rails apart thinking I'd leave space for the prop spinner. There was plenty of room, but I will leave that set alone. For the rest of my planes I will be mounting the hangars very close or completely together.

Screws

On the left side I only used two standard coated screws instead of four and they are holding fine. I am not sure of what size they are because they were not in a box, but they are like a basic drywall screw. Make sure your screws as flush or counter sunk or the hook will catch on them.

Final thoughts

I know this design may not be the best, use too much plastic, be overkill, or have many other flaws. I had fun making and testing them. I will keep tweaking them as I get feedback. As anyone with a large collection of airplanes knows, your collection is constantly changing. These work for me. And now I have room for more planes once I print more of these to get the rest of the larger single 2 blade prop planes off the ground.
